{
  "doc_id": "35775",
  "text": "Nevertheless, in all countries, fairness in financial contribution embraces two critical aspects; that of risk pooling between the healthy and the sick, and risk sharing across wealth and income levels [CITATION_1] . Regardless of income or wealth, risk sharing refers to the premise that equity does not mean equal contributions from all, but that contributions are greater from those who have more financial resources. However, citizens do not usually pay too much attention on the figures or meanings hidden in government reports, instead, they focus on what they can benefit from the policy, such as the proportion of the subsidies and whether they will fall into impoverishment after paying a medical bill.",
